<!--l. 1237--><p class="noindent">
</p><h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a id="x1-26000I"></a>Elliptic integrals</h5>
<a id="Q1-1-50"></a>
<a id="dx1-26001"></a>
<!--l. 1242--><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">EllipticK(k) </span>function returns the complete elliptic integral of the first kind, i.e. the definite
integral between 0 and pi/2 of the function <span class="cmbx-10">(1-(k*sin(p))**2)**(-0.5)</span>. The domain of <span class="cmbx-10">k </span>is -1 to 1
(exclusive).
<!--l. 1246--></p><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">EllipticE(k) </span>function returns the complete elliptic integral of the second kind, i.e. the definite
integral between 0 and pi/2 of the function <span class="cmbx-10">(1-(k*sin(p))**2)**0.5</span>. The domain of <span class="cmbx-10">k </span>is -1 to 1
(inclusive).
<!--l. 1250--></p><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">EllipticPi(n,k) </span>function returns the complete elliptic integral of the third kind, i.e. the definite integral
between 0 and pi/2 of the function <span class="cmbx-10">(1-(k*sin(p))**2)**(-0.5)/(1-n*sin(p)**2)</span>. The parameter <span class="cmbx-10">n </span>must be less
than 1, while <span class="cmbx-10">k </span>must lie between -1 and 1 (exclusive). Note that by definition EllipticPi(0,k) == EllipticK(k) for all
possible values of <span class="cmbx-10">k</span>.
</p><h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a id="x1-27000I"></a>Random number generator</h5>
<a id="Q1-1-52"></a>
<a id="dx1-27001"></a>
<a id="dx1-27002"></a>
<!--l. 1261--><p class="noindent">The function <span class="cmbx-10">rand() </span>produces a sequence of pseudo-random numbers between 0 and 1 using an algorithm from P.
L'Ecuyer and S. Cote, <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>Implementing a random number package with splitting facilities<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>, ACM Transactions on
Mathematical Software, 17:98-111 (1991).
