<!--l. 3061--><p class="noindent">The result is similar to using a <span class="cmbx-10">points </span>plot with variable size points and pointstyle 7, except that the circles will
scale with the x axis range. See also <span class="cmbx-10">set object circle (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-258000III"><span class="cmbx-10">179</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set object circle --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-67002"></a> and <span class="cmbx-10">fillstyle (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-297000III"><span class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fillstyle --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-67003"></a>.
</p><h3 class="likesectionHead"><a id="x1-68000II"></a>Ellipses</h3>
<a id="Q1-1-133"></a>
<a id="dx1-68001"></a>
<!--l. 3070--><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">ellipses </span>style plots an ellipse at each data point. This style is
only relevant for 2D plotting. Each ellipse is described in terms of its center, major and minor diameters, and the
angle between its major diameter and the x axis.

</p><div class="figure">
    <img src="http://www.gnuplotting.org/figs/man46_ellipses.png" alt="Ellipses"><p class="caption">
        <strong>Fig. 8 </strong>Plot style ellipses
    </p>
</div>

<!--l. 3077--><p class="noindent"></p><pre><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;2</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;columns:</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;x</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;y</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;3</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;columns:</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;x</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;y</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;major_diam</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;4</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;columns:</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;x</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;y</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;major_diam</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;minor_diam</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;5</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;columns:</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;x</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;y</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;major_diam</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;minor_diam</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;angle</span>
<!--l. 3082--></pre>
<!--l. 3085--><p class="noindent">If only two input columns are present, they are taken as the coordinates of the centers, and the ellipses will be
drawn with the default extent (see <span class="cmbx-10">set style ellipse (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-304000III"><span class="cmbx-10">206</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style ellipse --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-68002"></a>). The orientation of the ellipse, which
is defined as the angle between the major diameter and the plot's x axis, is taken from the default
ellipse style (see <span class="cmbx-10">set style ellipse (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-304000III"><span class="cmbx-10">206</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style ellipse --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-68003"></a>). If three input columns are provided, the third column is
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
used for both diameters. The orientation angle defaults to zero. If four columns are present, they are
interpreted as x, y, major diameter, minor diameter. Note that these are diameters, not radii. An
optional 5th column may be used to specify the orientation angle in degrees. The ellipses will also
be drawn with their default extent if either of the supplied diameters in the 3-4-5 column form is
negative.
<!--l. 3099--></p><p class="noindent">In all of the above cases, optional variable color data may be given in an additional last (3th, 4th, 5th or 6th)
column. See <span class="cmbx-10">colorspec (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-42000I"><span class="cmbx-10">40</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colorspec --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-68004"></a> for further information.
<!--l. 3103--></p><p class="noindent">By default, the major diameter is interpreted in the units of the plot's horizontal axis (x or x2) while the minor
diameter in that of the vertical (y or y2). This implies that if the x and y axis scales are not equal, then the
major/minor diameter ratio will no longer be correct after rotation. This behavior can be changed with the <span class="cmbx-10">units</span>
keyword, however.
<!--l. 3109--></p><p class="noindent">There are three alternatives: if <span class="cmbx-10">units xy </span>is included in the plot specification, the axes will be scaled as described
above. <span class="cmbx-10">units xx </span>ensures that both diameters are interpreted in units of the x axis, while <span class="cmbx-10">units yy </span>means that both
diameters are interpreted in units of the y axis. In the latter two cases the ellipses will have the correct aspect ratio,
even if the plot is resized.
<!--l. 3116--></p><p class="noindent">If <span class="cmbx-10">units </span>is omitted, the default setting will be used, which is equivalent to <span class="cmbx-10">units xy</span>. This can be redefined by <span class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">style ellipse</span>.
<!--l. 3119--></p><p class="noindent">Example (draws ellipses, cycling through the available line types):
<!--l. 3122--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">plot</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">'data'</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;using</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">1</span><span class="o">:</span><span class="n">2</span><span class="o">:</span><span class="n">3</span><span class="o">:</span><span class="n">4</span><span class="o">:(</span><span class="n">0</span><span class="o">):</span><span class="n">0</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;with</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;ellipses</span></span>
<!--l. 3124--></pre>
<!--l. 3127--><p class="noindent">See also <span class="cmbx-10">set object ellipse (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-257000III"><span class="cmbx-10">178</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set object ellipse --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-68005"></a>, <span class="cmbx-10">set style ellipse (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-304000III"><span class="cmbx-10">206</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set style ellipse --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-68006"></a> and <span class="cmbx-10">fillstyle (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-297000III"><span class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fillstyle --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-68007"></a>.
</p><h3 class="likesectionHead"><a id="x1-69000II"></a>Dots</h3>
<a id="Q1-1-135"></a>
<a id="dx1-69001"></a>
<!--l. 3136--><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">dots </span>style plots a tiny dot at each point; this is useful for scatter
plots with many points. Either 1 or 2 columns of input data are required in 2D. Three columns are required in
3D.
<!--l. 3141--></p><p class="noindent">For some terminals (post, pdf) the size of the dot can be controlled by changing the linewidth.

</p><div class="figure">
    <img src="http://www.gnuplotting.org/figs/man46_dots.png" alt="Dots"><p class="caption">
        <strong>Fig. 9 </strong>Plot style dots
    </p>
</div>

<!--l. 3145--><p class="noindent"></p><pre><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;1</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;column</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;y</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;#</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;x</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;is</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;row</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;number</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;2</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;columns:</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;x</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;y</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;3</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;columns:</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;x</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;y</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;z</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;#</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;3D</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;only</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;(splot)</span>
<!--l. 3149--></pre>
<!--l. 3152--><p class="noindent">
</p><h3 class="likesectionHead"><a id="x1-70000II"></a>Filledcurves</h3>
<a id="Q1-1-137"></a>
<a id="dx1-70001"></a>
<!--l. 3160--><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">filledcurves </span>style is only relevant to 2D plotting. Three
variants are possible. The first two variants require either a function or two columns of input data, and may be
further modified by the options listed below.

</p><div class="figure">
    <img src="http://www.gnuplotting.org/figs/man46_filledcurves.png" alt="Filledcurves"><p class="caption">
        <strong>Fig. 10 </strong>Plot style filledcurves
    </p>
</div>

<!--l. 3165--><p class="noindent">Syntax:
<!--l. 3168--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">plot</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">...</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">with</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;filledcurves</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">[</span><span class="p">option</span><span class="o">]</span></span>
<!--l. 3170--></pre>
<!--l. 3173--><p class="noindent">where the option can be one of the following
<!--l. 3176--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">[</span><span class="p">closed</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span><span class="p">above</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">below</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">x1</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">x2</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">y1</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">y2</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">r</span><span class="o">}[=&lt;</span><span class="p">a</span><span class="o">&gt;]</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">xy</span><span class="o">=&lt;</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">&gt;,&lt;</span><span class="p">y</span><span class="o">&gt;]</span></span>
<!--l. 3179--></pre>
<!--l. 3182--><p class="noindent">The first variant, <span class="cmbx-10">closed</span>, treats the curve itself as a closed polygon. This is the default if there are two columns of
input data.
<!--l. 3185--></p><p class="noindent">The second variant is to fill the area between the curve and a given axis, a horizontal or vertical line, or a
point.
<!--l. 3189--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;filledcurves</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;closed</span></span><span class="C"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">...</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">just</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;filled</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;closed</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;curve</span><span class="o">,</span></span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;filledcurves</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;x1</span></span><span class="C"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">...</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">x1</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;axis</span><span class="o">,</span></span></span><span class="p">
