<a id="dx1-76001"></a>
<!--l. 3509--><p class="noindent">Syntax:
<!--l. 3512--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;newhistogram</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="s">"&lt;title&gt;"</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span><span class="p">lt</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;linetype&gt;</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span><span class="p">fs</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;fillstyle&gt;</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span><span class="p">at</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="p">coord</span><span class="o">&gt;}</span></span>
<!--l. 3514--></pre>
<!--l. 3517--><p class="noindent">More than one set of histograms can appear in a single plot. In this case you can force a gap between them, and a
separate label for each set, by using the <span class="cmbx-10">newhistogram </span>command. For example
