</p><h3 class="likesectionHead"><a id="x1-126000III"></a>Plot</h3>
<a id="Q1-1-248"></a>
<a id="dx1-126001"></a>
<!--l. 5316--><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>is the primary command for drawing plots with <span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>. It creates plots of functions and data in many, many
ways. <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>is used to draw 2D functions and data; <span class="cmbx-10">splot </span>draws 2D projections of 3D surfaces and data. <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and
<span class="cmbx-10">splot </span>offer many features in common; see <span class="cmbx-10">splot (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-370000III"><span class="cmbx-10">231</span><!--tex4ht:ref: splot --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-126002"></a> for differences. Note specifically that although the
<span class="cmbx-10">binary </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">binary list</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>variation does work for both <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, there are small differences between
them.
