</tr><tr style="vertical-align: baseline;" id="TBL-10-11-"><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-11-1" class="td11"> 256 </td><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-11-2" class="td11">no effect</td><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-11-3" class="td11">  top left back    </td>
</tr><tr style="vertical-align: baseline;" id="TBL-10-12-"><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-12-1" class="td11"> 512 </td><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-12-2" class="td11">no effect</td><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-12-3" class="td11">  top right back   </td>
</tr><tr style="vertical-align: baseline;" id="TBL-10-13-"><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-13-1" class="td11">1024</td><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-13-2" class="td11">no effect</td><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-13-3" class="td11">  top left front    </td>
</tr><tr style="vertical-align: baseline;" id="TBL-10-14-"><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-14-1" class="td11">2048</td><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-14-2" class="td11">no effect</td><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-14-3" class="td11">  top right front   </td>
</tr><tr class="hline"><td><hr></td><td><hr></td><td><hr></td></tr><tr style="vertical-align: baseline;" id="TBL-10-15-"><td style="white-space: nowrap; text-align: center;" id="TBL-10-15-1" class="td11">    </td>
</tr></tbody></table></div>
<!--l. 8236--><p class="noindent">Various bits or combinations of bits may be added together in the command.
<!--l. 8238--></p><p class="noindent">The default is 31, which is all four sides for <span class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, and base and z axis for <span class="cmbx-10">splot</span>.
<!--l. 8241--></p><p class="noindent">In 2D plots the border is normally drawn on top of all plots elements (<span class="cmbx-10">front</span>). If you want the border to be drawn
behind the plot elements, use <span class="cmbx-10">set border back</span>.
<!--l. 8245--></p><p class="noindent">Using the optional <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>line_style<span class="cmmi-10">&gt;</span>, <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>line_type<span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>and <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>line_width<span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>specifiers, the way the border lines are drawn can
be influenced (limited by what the current terminal driver supports).
<!--l. 8249--></p><p class="noindent">For <span class="cmbx-10">plot</span>, tics may be drawn on edges other than bottom and left by enabling the second axes – see <span class="cmbx-10">set xtics</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-335000III"><span class="cmbx-10">220</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set xtics --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-199003"></a> for details.
<!--l. 8252--></p><p class="noindent">If a <span class="cmbx-10">splot </span>draws only on the base, as is the case with <span class="cmtt-10">"</span><span class="cmbx-10">unset surface; set contour base</span><span class="cmtt-10">"</span>, then the verticals and
the top are not drawn even if they are specified.
<!--l. 8256--></p><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">set grid </span>options 'back', 'front' and 'layerdefault' also control the order in which the border lines are drawn
with respect to the output of the plotted data.
<!--l. 8260--></p><p class="noindent">Examples:
<!--l. 8262--></p><p class="noindent">Draw default borders: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;border</span></span>
<!--l. 8266--></pre>
<!--l. 8269--><p class="noindent">Draw only the left and bottom (<span class="cmbx-10">plot</span>) or both front and back bottom left (<span class="cmbx-10">splot</span>) borders: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;border</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">3</span></span>
<!--l. 8274--></pre>
<!--l. 8277--><p class="noindent">Draw a complete box around a <span class="cmbx-10">splot</span>: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;border</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">4095</span></span>
<!--l. 8281--></pre>
<!--l. 8284--><p class="noindent">Draw a topless box around a <span class="cmbx-10">splot</span>, omitting the front vertical: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;border</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">127</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">256</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">512</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="C">#</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;or</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;border</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;1023-128</span></span>
<!--l. 8288--></pre>
<!--l. 8291--><p class="noindent">Draw only the top and right borders for a <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and label them as axes: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">unset</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;xtics</span><span class="o">;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">unset</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;ytics</span><span class="o">;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;x2tics</span><span class="o">;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;y2tics</span><span class="o">;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;border</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">12</span></span>
<!--l. 8295--></pre>
<!--l. 8298--><p class="noindent">
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-200000III"></a>Boxwidth</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-396"></a>
<a id="dx1-200001"></a>
<!--l. 8306--><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">set boxwidth </span>command is used to set the default width of boxes in the <span class="cmbx-10">boxes</span>, <span class="cmbx-10">boxerrorbars</span>, <span class="cmbx-10">boxplot</span>,
<span class="cmbx-10">candlesticks </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">histograms </span>styles.
<!--l. 8309--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;boxwidth</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{&lt;</span><span class="p">width</span><span class="o">&gt;}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span><span class="p">absolute</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="p">relative</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">show</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;boxwidth</span></span>
<!--l. 8314--></pre>
<!--l. 8317--><p class="noindent">By default, adjacent boxes are extended in width until they touch each other. A different default width may be
specified using the <span class="cmbx-10">set boxwidth </span>command. <span class="cmbx-10">Relative </span>widths are interpreted as being a fraction of this default
width.
<!--l. 8321--></p><p class="noindent">An explicit value for the boxwidth is interpreted as being a number of units along the current x axis
(<span class="cmbx-10">absolute</span>) unless the modifier <span class="cmbx-10">relative </span>is given. If the x axis is a log-scale (see <span class="cmbx-10">set log (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-239000III"><span class="cmbx-10">168</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set log --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-200002"></a>) then the
value of boxwidth is truly <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>absolute<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>only at x=1; this physical width is maintained everywhere along
the axis (i.e. the boxes do not become narrower the value of x increases). If the range spanned by
a log scale x axis is far from x=1, some experimentation may be required to find a useful value of
boxwidth.
<!--l. 8329--></p><p class="noindent">The default is superseded by explicit width information taken from an extra data column in styles <span class="cmbx-10">boxes </span>or
<span class="cmbx-10">boxerrorbars</span>. In a four-column data set, the fourth column will be interpreted as the box width unless the width
is set to -2.0, in which case the width will be calculated automatically. See <span class="cmbx-10">style boxes (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-63000II"><span class="cmbx-10">54</span><!--tex4ht:ref: style boxes --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-200003"></a> and <span class="cmbx-10">style</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">boxerrorbars (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-62000II"><span class="cmbx-10">54</span><!--tex4ht:ref: style boxerrorbars --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-200004"></a> for more details.
<!--l. 8335--></p><p class="noindent">To set the box width to automatic use the command </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;boxwidth</span></span>
<!--l. 8339--></pre>
<!--l. 8342--><p class="noindent">or, for four-column data, </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;boxwidth</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="n">2</span></span>
<!--l. 8346--></pre>
<!--l. 8349--><p class="noindent">The same effect can be achieved with the <span class="cmbx-10">using </span>keyword in <span class="cmbx-10">plot</span>: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">plot</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">'file'</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;using</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">1</span><span class="o">:</span><span class="n">2</span><span class="o">:</span><span class="n">3</span><span class="o">:</span><span class="n">4</span><span class="o">:(-</span><span class="n">2</span><span class="o">)</span></span>
<!--l. 8353--></pre>
<!--l. 8356--><p class="noindent">To set the box width to half of the automatic size use </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;boxwidth</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">0.5</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;relative</span></span>
<!--l. 8360--></pre>
<!--l. 8363--><p class="noindent">To set the box width to an absolute value of 2 use </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;boxwidth</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">2</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;absolute</span></span>
<!--l. 8367--></pre>
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-201000III"></a>Clabel</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-398"></a>
<a id="dx1-201001"></a>
<!--l. 8379--><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will vary the linetype used for each contour level when clabel is set. When this option on (the default), a
legend labels each linestyle with the z level it represents. It is not possible at present to separate the contour labels
from the surface key.
<!--l. 8384--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clabel</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="s">'&lt;format&gt;'</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">unset</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clabel</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">show</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clabel</span></span>
<!--l. 8390--></pre>
<!--l. 8393--><p class="noindent">The default for the format string is %8.3g, which gives three decimal places. This may produce poor label alignment
if the key is altered from its default configuration.
<!--l. 8397--></p><p class="noindent">The first contour linetype, or only contour linetype when clabel is off, is the surface linetype +1; contour points are
the same style as surface points.
<!--l. 8400--></p><p class="noindent">See also <span class="cmbx-10">set contour (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-206000III"><span class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set contour --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-201002"></a>.
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-202000III"></a>Clip</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-400"></a>
<a id="dx1-202001"></a>
<a id="dx1-202002"></a>
<!--l. 8413--><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>can clip data points and lines that are near the boundaries of a graph.
<!--l. 8416--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clip</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="p">clip</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="p">type</span><span class="o">&gt;</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">unset</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clip</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="p">clip</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="p">type</span><span class="o">&gt;</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">show</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clip</span></span>
<!--l. 8422--></pre>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<!--l. 8425--><p class="noindent">Three clip types for points and lines are supported by <span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot</span>: <span class="cmbx-10">points</span>, <span class="cmbx-10">one</span>, and <span class="cmbx-10">two</span>. One, two, or all three
clip types may be active for a single graph. Note that clipping of color filled quadrangles drawn by
<span class="cmbx-10">pm3d </span>maps and surfaces is not controlled by this command, but by <span class="cmbx-10">set pm3d clip1in </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">set pm3d</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">clip4in</span>.
<!--l. 8432--></p><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">points </span>clip type forces <span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to clip (actually, not plot at all) data points that fall within but too close to
the boundaries. This is done so that large symbols used for points will not extend outside the boundary lines.
Without clipping points near the boundaries, the plot may look bad. Adjusting the x and y ranges may give similar
results.
<!--l. 8438--></p><p class="noindent">Setting the <span class="cmbx-10">one </span>clip type causes <span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>to draw a line segment which has only one of its two endpoints within the
graph. Only the in-range portion of the line is drawn. The alternative is to not draw any portion of the line
segment.
<!--l. 8443--></p><p class="noindent">Some lines may have both endpoints out of range, but pass through the graph. Setting the <span class="cmbx-10">two </span>clip-type allows the
visible portion of these lines to be drawn.
<!--l. 8447--></p><p class="noindent">In no case is a line drawn outside the graph.
<!--l. 8449--></p><p class="noindent">The defaults are <span class="cmbx-10">noclip points</span>, <span class="cmbx-10">clip one</span>, and <span class="cmbx-10">noclip two</span>.
<!--l. 8451--></p><p class="noindent">To check the state of all forms of clipping, use </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">show</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clip</span></span>
<!--l. 8455--></pre>
<!--l. 8458--><p class="noindent">For backward compatibility with older versions, the following forms are also permitted: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clip</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">unset</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;clip</span></span>
<!--l. 8464--></pre>
<!--l. 8467--><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">set clip </span>is synonymous with <span class="cmbx-10">set clip points</span>; <span class="cmbx-10">unset clip </span>turns off all three types of clipping.
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-203000III"></a>Cntrparam</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-402"></a>
<a id="dx1-203001"></a>
<!--l. 8477--><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">set cntrparam </span>controls the generation of contours and their smoothness for a contour plot. <span class="cmbx-10">show contour</span>
displays current settings of <span class="cmbx-10">cntrparam </span>as well as <span class="cmbx-10">contour</span>.
<!--l. 8481--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;cntrparam</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">linear</span></span><span class="p">
