<!--l. 8859--><p class="noindent">The first <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>will recognize only the first datum in the <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>3 ?<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>line. It will use the single-datum-on-a-line convention
that the line number is <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>x<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>and the datum is <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>y<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>, so the point will be plotted (in this case erroneously) at
(2,3).
<!--l. 8864--></p><p class="noindent">The second and third <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>commands will correctly ignore the middle line. The plotted line will connect the points
at (2,20) and (4,40).
<!--l. 8867--></p><p class="noindent">The fourth <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>will also correctly ignore the middle line, but the plotted line will not connect the points at (2,20)
and (4,40).
<!--l. 8870--></p><p class="noindent">There is no default character for <span class="cmbx-10">missing</span>, but in many cases any non-parsible string of characters found where a
numerical value is expected will be treated as missing data.
<!--l. 8874--></p><p class="noindent">
</p><h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a id="x1-212000III"></a>Set datafile separator</h5>
<a id="Q1-1-420"></a>
<a id="dx1-212001"></a>
<!--l. 8881--><p class="noindent">The command <span class="cmbx-10">set datafile separator </span><span class="cmtt-10">"</span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">char</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt;</span><span class="cmtt-10">" </span>tells <span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>that data fields in subsequent input
files are separated by <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>char<span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>rather than by whitespace. The most common use is to read in csv
(comma-separated value) files written by spreadsheet or database programs. By default data fields are separated by
whitespace.
<!--l. 8887--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;datafile</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;separator</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="s">"&lt;char&gt;"</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">whitespace</span><span class="o">}</span></span>
<!--l. 8891--></pre>
<!--l. 8894--><p class="noindent">Examples: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="C">#</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;Input</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;file</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;contains</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;tab-separated</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="C">&nbsp;fields</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;datafile</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;separator</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">"\t"</span></span>
<!--l. 8899--></pre>
