</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">show</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;line</span></span>
<!--l. 13037--></pre>
<!--l. 13040--><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">default </span>sets all line style parameters to those of the linetype with that same index.
<!--l. 13043--></p><p class="noindent">If the linestyle <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>index<span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>already exists, only the given parameters are changed while all others are preserved. If not,
all undefined values are set to the default values.
<!--l. 13047--></p><p class="noindent">Line styles created by this mechanism do not replace the default linetype styles; both may be used. Line styles are
temporary. They are lost whenever you execute a <span class="cmbx-10">reset </span>command. To redefine the linetype itself, please see <span class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">linetype (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-235000III"><span class="cmbx-10">166</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set linetype --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-301007"></a>.
<!--l. 13052--></p><p class="noindent">The line and point types default to the index value. The exact symbol that is drawn for that index value may vary
from one terminal type to another.
<!--l. 13055--></p><p class="noindent">The line width and point size are multipliers for the current terminal's default width and size (but note that
<span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>point_size<span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>here is unaffected by the multiplier given by the command<span class="cmbx-10">set pointsize</span>).
<!--l. 13059--></p><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">pointinterval </span>controls the spacing between points in a plot drawn with style <span class="cmbx-10">linespoints</span>. The
default is 0 (every point is drawn). For example, <span class="cmbx-10">set style line N pi 3 </span>defines a linestyle that uses
pointtype N, pointsize and linewidth equal to the current defaults for the terminal, and will draw every
3rd point in plots using <span class="cmbx-10">with linespoints</span>. A negative value for the interval is treated the same as a
positive value, except that some terminals will try to interrupt the line where it passes through the point
symbol.
<!--l. 13067--></p><p class="noindent">Not all terminals support the <span class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">pointsize </span>features; if not supported, the option will be
ignored.
<!--l. 13070--></p><p class="noindent">Terminal-independent colors may be assigned using either <span class="cmbx-10">linecolor </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">colorspec</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>or <span class="cmbx-10">linetype </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">colorspec</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt;</span>,
abbreviated <span class="cmbx-10">lc </span>or <span class="cmbx-10">lt</span>. This requires giving a RGB color triple, a known palette color name, a fractional index
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
into the current palette, or a constant value from the current mapping of the palette onto cbrange.
See <span class="cmbx-10">colors (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-41000I"><span class="cmbx-10">39</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colors --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-301008"></a>, <span class="cmbx-10">colorspec (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-42000I"><span class="cmbx-10">40</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colorspec --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-301009"></a>, <span class="cmbx-10">set palette (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-274000III"><span class="cmbx-10">187</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set palette --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-301010"></a>, <span class="cmbx-10">colornames (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-205000III"><span class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colornames --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-301011"></a>, <span class="cmbx-10">cbrange</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-367000III"><span class="cmbx-10">230</span><!--tex4ht:ref: cbrange --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-301012"></a>.
<!--l. 13077--></p><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">set style line </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">n</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span><span class="cmbx-10">linetype </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">lt</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>will set both a terminal-dependent dot/dash pattern and color. The
commands<span class="cmbx-10">set style line </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">n</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span><span class="cmbx-10">linecolor </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">colorspec</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>or <span class="cmbx-10">set style line </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">n</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span><span class="cmbx-10">linetype </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">colorspec</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>will set a
new line color while leaving the existing dot-dash pattern unchanged.
<!--l. 13082--></p><p class="noindent">In 3d mode (<span class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command), the special keyword <span class="cmbx-10">palette </span>is allowed as a shorthand for <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>linetype palette z<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>. The
color value corresponds to the z-value (elevation) of the splot, and varies smoothly along a line or
surface.
<!--l. 13086--></p><p class="noindent">Examples: Suppose that the default lines for indices 1, 2, and 3 are red, green, and blue, respectively,
and the default point shapes for the same indices are a square, a cross, and a triangle, respectively.
Then
<!--l. 13092--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;line</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">1</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;lt</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">2</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;lw</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">2</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;pt</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">3</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;ps</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">0.5</span></span>
<!--l. 13094--></pre>
<!--l. 13097--><p class="noindent">defines a new linestyle that is green and twice the default width and a new pointstyle that is a half-sized triangle.
The commands
<!--l. 13101--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;function</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;lines</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">plot</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;f</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">)</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">lt</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">3</span><span class="o">,</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">g</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">)</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">ls</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">1</span></span>
<!--l. 13104--></pre>
<!--l. 13107--><p class="noindent">will create a plot of f(x) using the default blue line and a plot of g(x) using the user-defined wide green line.
Similarly the commands
<!--l. 13111--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;function</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;linespoints</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">plot</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;p</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">)</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">lt</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">1</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;pt</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">3</span><span class="o">,</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">q</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">)</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">ls</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">1</span></span>
<!--l. 13114--></pre>
<!--l. 13117--><p class="noindent">will create a plot of p(x) using the default triangles connected by a red line and q(x) using small triangles connected
by a green line.
<!--l. 13121--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">splot</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;sin</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="p">sqrt</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="p">y</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">y</span><span class="o">))/</span><span class="p">sqrt</span><span class="o">(</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">x</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="p">y</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">y</span><span class="o">)</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">w</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;l</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;pal</span></span>
<!--l. 13123--></pre>
<!--l. 13126--><p class="noindent">creates a surface plot using smooth colors according to <span class="cmbx-10">palette</span>. Note, that this works only on some terminals. See
also <span class="cmbx-10">set palette (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-274000III"><span class="cmbx-10">187</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set palette --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-301013"></a>, <span class="cmbx-10">set pm3d (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-265000III"><span class="cmbx-10">182</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set pm3d --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-301014"></a>.
<!--l. 13130--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;line</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">10</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;linetype</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">1</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;linecolor</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;rgb</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">"cyan"</span></span>
<!--l. 13132--></pre>
<!--l. 13135--><p class="noindent">will assign linestyle 10 to be a solid cyan line on any terminal that supports rgb colors.
<!--l. 13138--></p><p class="noindent">
</p><h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a id="x1-302000III"></a>Set style circle</h5>
<a id="Q1-1-600"></a>
<!--l. 13147--><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;circle</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">radius</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">graph</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="p">screen</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;&lt;</span><span class="p">R</span><span class="o">&gt;}</span></span>
<!--l. 13151--></pre>
<!--l. 13154--><p class="noindent">This command sets the default radius used in plot style <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>with circles<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>. It applies to data plots with only 2 columns
of data (x,y) and to function plots. The default is <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>set style circle radius graph 0.02<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 13158--></p><p class="noindent">
</p><h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a id="x1-303000III"></a>Set style rectangle</h5>
<a id="Q1-1-602"></a>
<!--l. 13167--><p class="noindent">Rectangles defined with the <span class="cmbx-10">set object </span>command can have individual styles. However, if the object
is not assigned a private style then it inherits a default that is taken from the <span class="cmbx-10">set style rectangle</span>
command.
<!--l. 13171--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;rectangle</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">front</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="p">back</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span><span class="p">lw</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="p">linewidth</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;lw&gt;</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">fillcolor</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;colorspec&gt;</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span><span class="p">fs</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;fillstyle&gt;</span><span class="o">}</span></span>
<!--l. 13176--></pre>
<!--l. 13179--><p class="noindent">See <span class="cmbx-10">colorspec (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-42000I"><span class="cmbx-10">40</span><!--tex4ht:ref: colorspec --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-303001"></a> and <span class="cmbx-10">fillstyle (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-297000III"><span class="cmbx-10">202</span><!--tex4ht:ref: fillstyle --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-303002"></a>. <span class="cmbx-10">fillcolor </span>may be abbreviated as <span class="cmbx-10">fc</span>.
<!--l. 13181--></p><p class="noindent">Examples: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;rectangle</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;back</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;fc</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;rgb</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">"white"</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;fs</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;solid</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">1.0</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;border</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;lt</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="n">1</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;rectangle</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;fc</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;linsestyle</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">3</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;fs</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;pattern</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">2</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;noborder</span></span>
<!--l. 13186--></pre>
<!--l. 13189--><p class="noindent">The default values correspond to solid fill with the background color and a black border.
<!--l. 13192--></p><p class="noindent">
</p><h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a id="x1-304000III"></a>Set style ellipse</h5>
<a id="Q1-1-604"></a>
<!--l. 13200--><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;style</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;ellipse</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">units</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;xx</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="p">xy</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="p">yy</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">size</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">graph</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="p">screen</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;&lt;</span><span class="p">a</span><span class="o">&gt;,</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{{</span><span class="p">graph</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="p">screen</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;&lt;</span><span class="p">b</span><span class="o">&gt;}}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">angle</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;angle&gt;</span><span class="o">}</span></span>
<!--l. 13206--></pre>
<!--l. 13209--><p class="noindent">This command governs whether the diameters of ellipses are interpreted in the same units or not. Default is <span class="cmbx-10">xy</span>,
which means that the major diameter (first axis) of ellipses will be interpreted in the same units as the x (or x2)
axis, while the minor (second) diameter in those of the y (or y2) axis. In this mode the ratio of the ellipse axes
depends on the scales of the plot axes and aspect ratio of the plot. When set to <span class="cmbx-10">xx </span>or <span class="cmbx-10">yy</span>, both axes of all
ellipses will be interpreted in the same units. This means that the ratio of the axes of the plotted
ellipses will be correct even after rotation, but either their vertical or horizontal extent will not be
correct.
<!--l. 13221--></p><p class="noindent">This is a global setting that affects all ellipses, both those defined as objects and those generated with
the <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>command, however, the value of <span class="cmbx-10">units </span>can also be redefined on a per-plot and per-object
basis.
<!--l. 13225--></p><p class="noindent">It is also possible to set a default size for ellipses with the <span class="cmbx-10">size </span>keyword. This default size applies to data plots with
only 2 columns of data (x,y) and to function plots. The two values are interpreted as the major and minor diameters
(as opposed to semi-major and semi-minor axes) of the ellipse.
<!--l. 13231--></p><p class="noindent">The default is <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>set style ellipse size graph 0.05,0.03<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>.
<!--l. 13233--></p><p class="noindent">Last, but not least it is possible to set the default orientation with the <span class="cmbx-10">angle </span>keyword. The orientation, which
is defined as the angle between the major axis of the ellipse and the plot's x axis, must be given in
degrees.
<!--l. 13237--></p><p class="noindent">For defining ellipse objects, see <span class="cmbx-10">set object ellipse (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-257000III"><span class="cmbx-10">178</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set object ellipse --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-304001"></a>; for the 2D plot style, see <span class="cmbx-10">ellipses (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-68000II"><span class="cmbx-10">59</span><!--tex4ht:ref: ellipses --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-304002"></a>.
<!--l. 13240--></p><p class="noindent">
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-305000III"></a>Surface</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-606"></a>
<a id="dx1-305001"></a>
<a id="dx1-305002"></a>
<!--l. 13252--><p class="noindent">The command <span class="cmbx-10">set surface </span>controls the display of surfaces by <span class="cmbx-10">splot</span>.
<!--l. 13254--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;surface</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">unset</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;surface</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">show</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;surface</span></span>
<!--l. 13260--></pre>
<!--l. 13263--><p class="noindent">The surface is drawn with the style specified by <span class="cmbx-10">with</span>, or else the appropriate style, data or function.
<!--l. 13266--></p><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">unset surface </span>will cause <span class="cmbx-10">splot </span>to not draw points or lines corresponding to any of the function or data file points.
If you want to turn off the surface for an individual function or data file while leaving the others active, use the
<span class="cmbx-10">nosurface </span>keyword in the <span class="cmbx-10">splot </span>command. Contours may still be drawn on the surface, depending on the <span class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">contour </span>option. The combination <span class="cmbx-10">unset surface; set contour base </span>is useful for displaying contours on the grid
base. See also <span class="cmbx-10">set contour (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-206000III"><span class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set contour --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-305003"></a>.
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-306000III"></a>Table</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-608"></a>
<a id="dx1-306001"></a>
<!--l. 13279--><p class="noindent">When <span class="cmbx-10">table </span>mode is enabled, <span class="cmbx-10">plot </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">splot </span>commands print out a multicolumn ASCII table of X Y <span class="cmsy-10">{</span>Z<span class="cmsy-10">} </span>R values
rather than creating an actual plot on the current terminal. The character R takes on one of three values:
<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>i<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>if the point is in the active range, <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>o<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>if it is out-of-range, or <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>u<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>if it is undefined. The data
format is determined by the format of the axis labels (see <span class="cmbx-10">set format (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-221000III"><span class="cmbx-10">152</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set format --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-306002"></a>), and the columns
are separated by single spaces. This can be useful if you want to generate contours and then save
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
them for further use, perhaps for plotting with <span class="cmbx-10">plot</span>; see <span class="cmbx-10">set contour (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-206000III"><span class="cmbx-10">141</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set contour --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-306003"></a> for example. The
same method can be used to save interpolated data (see <span class="cmbx-10">set samples (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-291000III"><span class="cmbx-10">197</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set samples --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-306004"></a> and <span class="cmbx-10">set dgrid3d</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">(p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-216000III"><span class="cmbx-10">147</span><!--tex4ht:ref: set dgrid3d --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-306005"></a>).
<!--l. 13290--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;table</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="s">"outfile"</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">plot</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;whatever&gt;</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">unset</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;table</span></span>
<!--l. 13296--></pre>
<!--l. 13299--><p class="noindent">Tabular output is written to the named file, if any, otherwise it is written to the current value of <span class="cmbx-10">set output</span>. You
must explicitly <span class="cmbx-10">unset table </span>in order to go back to normal plotting on the current terminal.
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-307000III"></a>Terminal</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-610"></a>
<a id="dx1-307001"></a>
<a id="dx1-307002"></a>
<!--l. 13322--><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>supports many different graphics devices. Use <span class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>to tell <span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>what kind of output to
generate. Use <span class="cmbx-10">set output </span>to redirect that output to a file or device.
<!--l. 13326--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;terminal</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{&lt;</span><span class="p">terminal</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="p">type</span><span class="o">&gt;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">push</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">|</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="p">pop</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">show</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;terminal</span></span>
<!--l. 13331--></pre>
<!--l. 13334--><p class="noindent">If <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>terminal-type<span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>is omitted, <span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>will list the available terminal types. <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>terminal-type<span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>may be
abbreviated.
<!--l. 13337--></p><p class="noindent">If both <span class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">set output </span>are used together, it is safest to give <span class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>first, because some
terminals set a flag which is needed in some operating systems.
<!--l. 13341--></p><p class="noindent">Some terminals have many additional options. The options used by a previous invocation <span class="cmbx-10">set term </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">term</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt;</span>
<span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">options</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>of a given <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">term</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>are remembered, thus subsequent <span class="cmbx-10">set term </span><span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span><span class="cmbx-10">term</span><span class="cmmi-10">&gt; </span>does not reset them. This
helps in printing, for instance, when switching among different terminals — previous options don't have to be
repeated.
<!--l. 13347--></p><p class="noindent">The command <span class="cmbx-10">set term push </span>remembers the current terminal including its settings while <span class="cmbx-10">set term pop </span>restores
it. This is equivalent to <span class="cmbx-10">save term </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">load term</span>, but without accessing the filesystem. Therefore they can be
used to achieve platform independent restoring of the terminal after printing, for instance. After gnuplot's startup,
the default terminal or that from <span class="cmbx-10">startup </span>file is pushed automatically. Therefore portable scripts can rely that <span class="cmbx-10">set</span>
<span class="cmbx-10">term pop </span>restores the default terminal on a given platform unless another terminal has been pushed
explicitly.
<!--l. 13356--></p><p class="noindent">For more information, see the <span class="cmbx-10">complete list of terminals (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-384000IV"><span class="cmbx-10">240</span><!--tex4ht:ref: complete list of terminals --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-307003"></a>.
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-308000III"></a>Termoption</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-612"></a>
<a id="dx1-308001"></a>
<!--l. 13363--><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">set termoption </span>command allows you to change the behaviour of the current terminal without requiring a new
<span class="cmbx-10">set terminal </span>command. Only one option can be changed per command, and only a small number of options can be
changed this way. Currently the only options accepted are
