<!--l. 15875--><p class="noindent"><span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>honors the following resources for setting the dash style used for plotting lines. 0 means a solid line. A
two-digit number <span class="cmbx-10">jk </span>(<span class="cmbx-10">j </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">k </span>are <span class="cmmi-10">&gt;</span>= 1 and <span class="cmmi-10">&lt;</span>= 9) means a dashed line with a repeated pattern of <span class="cmbx-10">j </span>pixels on
followed by <span class="cmbx-10">k </span>pixels off. For example, '16' is a <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>dotted<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>line with one pixel on followed by six pixels off. More
elaborate on/off patterns can be specified with a four-digit value. For example, '4441' is four on, four off, four on,
one off. The default values shown below are for monochrome displays or monochrome rendering on color or grayscale
displays. For color displays, the default for each is 0 (solid line) except for <span class="cmbx-10">axisDashes </span>which defaults to a '16'
dotted line.
