<!--l. 16580--><p class="noindent">
</p><h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a id="x1-407000IV"></a>Requirements</h5>
<a id="Q1-1-809"></a>
<!--l. 16582--><p class="noindent">You need gnuplot module for ConTeXt
<!--l. 16583--></p><p class="noindent">     <a href="http://ctan.org/pkg/context-gnuplot"><span class="cmtt-10">http://ctan.org/pkg/context-gnuplot </span></a>
<!--l. 16586--></p><p class="noindent">and a recent version of ConTeXt. If you want to call gnuplot on-the-fly, you also need write18 enabled. In most TeX
distributions this can be set with shell_escape=t in texmf.cnf.
<!--l. 16590--></p><p class="noindent">See
<a href="http://wiki.contextgarden.net/Gnuplot"><span class="cmtt-10">http://wiki.contextgarden.net/Gnuplot </span></a>
for details about this terminal and for more exhaustive help &amp; examples.
<!--l. 16596--></p><p class="noindent">
</p><h5 class="likesubsubsectionHead"><a id="x1-408000IV"></a>Calling gnuplot from ConTeXt</h5>
<a id="Q1-1-811"></a>
<!--l. 16598--><p class="noindent">The easiest way to make plots in ConTeXt documents is </p><pre><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;\usemodule[gnuplot]</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;\starttext</span>
