<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-472000IV"></a>Tikz</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-939"></a>
<a id="dx1-472001"></a>
<!--l. 20187--><p class="noindent">This driver creates output for use with the TikZ package of graphics macros in TeX. It is currently implemented via
an external lua script, and <span class="cmbx-10">set term tikz </span>is a short form of the command <span class="cmbx-10">set term lua tikz</span>. See
<span class="cmbx-10">term lua (p.</span><span class="cmbx-10">&nbsp;</span><a href="#x1-438000IV"><span class="cmbx-10">274</span><!--tex4ht:ref: term lua --></a><span class="cmbx-10">)</span><a id="dx1-472002"></a> for more information. Use the command <span class="cmbx-10">set term tikz help </span>to print terminal
options.
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-473000IV"></a>Tkcanvas</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-941"></a>
<a id="dx1-473001"></a>
<!--l. 20201--><p class="noindent">This terminal driver generates Tk canvas widget commands based on Tcl/Tk (default) or Perl. To use it, rebuild
<span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>(after uncommenting or inserting the appropriate line in <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>term.h<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>), then
<!--l. 20206--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">gnuplot</span><span class="o">&gt;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;term</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;tkcanvas</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="o">{</span><span class="p">perltk</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;{</span><span class="p">interactive</span><span class="o">}</span></span><span class="p">
</span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">gnuplot</span><span class="o">&gt;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="o">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;output</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">'plot.file'</span></span>
<!--l. 20209--></pre>
<!--l. 20212--><p class="noindent">After invoking <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>wish<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>, execute the following sequence of Tcl/Tk commands:
<!--l. 20215--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre><span class="cmtt-10">%</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;source</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;plot.file</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">%</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;canvas</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;.c</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">%</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;pack</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;.c</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">%</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;gnuplot</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;.c</span>
<!--l. 20220--></pre>
<!--l. 20223--><p class="noindent">Or, for Perl/Tk use a program like this:
<!--l. 20226--></p><p class="noindent"></p><pre><span class="cmtt-10">use</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;Tk;</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">my</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;$top</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;=</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;MainWindow-&gt;new;</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">my</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;$c</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;=</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;$top-&gt;Canvas-&gt;pack;</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">my</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;$gnuplot</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;=</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;do</span><span class="cmtt-10">&nbsp;"plot.pl";</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">$gnuplot-&gt;($c);</span>
<span class="cmtt-10">MainLoop;</span>
<!--l. 20233--></pre>
<!--l. 20236--><p class="noindent">The code generated by <span class="cmbx-10">gnuplot </span>creates a procedure called <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>that takes the name of a canvas as its
argument. When the procedure is called, it clears the canvas, finds the size of the canvas and draws the plot in it,
scaled to fit.
<!--l. 20241--></p><p class="noindent">For 2-dimensional plotting (<span class="cmbx-10">plot</span>) two additional procedures are defined: <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot_plotarea<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>will return a list
containing the borders of the plotting area <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>xleft, xright, ytop, ybot<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>in canvas screen coordinates, while the ranges
of the two axes <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>x1min, x1max, y1min, y1max, x2min, x2max, y2min, y2max<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>in plot coordinates can be obtained
calling <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>gnuplot_axisranges<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>. If the <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>interactive<span class="cmtt-10">" </span>option is specified, mouse clicking on a line segment will print the
coordinates of its midpoint to stdout. Advanced actions can happen instead if the user supplies a procedure named
<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>user_gnuplot_coordinates<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>, which takes the following arguments: <span class="cmtt-10">"</span>win id x1s y1s x2s y2s x1e y1e x2e y2e x1m y1m
x2m y2m<span class="cmtt-10">"</span>, the name of the canvas and the id of the line segment followed by the coordinates of its start and end
point in the two possible axis ranges; the coordinates of the midpoint are only filled for logarithmic
axes.
<!--l. 20255--></p><p class="noindent">The current version of <span class="cmbx-10">tkcanvas </span>supports neither <span class="cmbx-10">multiplot </span>nor <span class="cmbx-10">replot</span>.
</p><h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-474000IV"></a>Tpic</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-943"></a>
                                                                                         
                                                                                         
<a id="dx1-474001"></a>
<!--l. 20265--><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">tpic </span>terminal driver supports the LaTeX picture environment with tpic <span class="cmsy-10">\</span>specials. It is an alternative to the
<span class="cmbx-10">latex </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">eepic </span>terminal drivers. Options are the point size, line width, and dot-dash interval.
<!--l. 20269--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;terminal</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;tpic</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;pointsize&gt;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;linewidth&gt;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">&lt;interval&gt;</span></span>
<!--l. 20273--></pre>
<!--l. 20276--><p class="noindent">where <span class="cmbx-10">pointsize </span>and <span class="cmbx-10">linewidth </span>are integers in milli-inches and <span class="cmbx-10">interval </span>is a float in inches. If a non-positive value
is specified, the default is chosen: pointsize = 40, linewidth = 6, interval = 0.1.
<!--l. 20280--></p><p class="noindent">All drivers for LaTeX offer a special way of controlling text positioning: If any text string begins with '<span class="cmsy-10">{</span>', you also
need to include a '<span class="cmsy-10">}</span>' at the end of the text, and the whole text will be centered both horizontally and vertically by
LaTeX. — If the text string begins with '[', you need to continue it with: a position specification (up to two out of
t,b,l,r), ']<span class="cmsy-10">{</span>', the text itself, and finally, '<span class="cmsy-10">}</span>'. The text itself may be anything LaTeX can typeset as an LR-box.
<span class="cmsy-10">\</span>rule<span class="cmsy-10">{}{}</span>'s may help for best positioning.
<!--l. 20288--></p><p class="noindent">Examples: About label positioning: Use gnuplot defaults (mostly sensible, but sometimes not really best):
</p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;title</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">'\LaTeX\</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;--</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;$</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;\gamma</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;$'</span></span>
<!--l. 20294--></pre> <p>Force centering both horizontally and vertically:</p> <pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;label</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">'{\LaTeX\</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;--</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;$</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;\gamma</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;$}'</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;at</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="n">0</span><span class="o">,</span><span class="n">0</span></span>
<!--l. 20300--></pre> <p>Specify own positioning (top here):</p> <pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;xlabel</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">'[t]{\LaTeX\</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;--</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;$</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;\gamma</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;$}'</span></span>
<!--l. 20306--></pre> <p>The other label – account for long ticlabels:</p> <pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;ylabel</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="s">'[r]{\LaTeX\</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;--</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;$</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;\gamma</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="s">&nbsp;$\rule{7mm}{0pt}}'</span></span>
<!--l. 20312--></pre>
<h4 class="likesubsectionHead"><a id="x1-475000IV"></a>Vgagl</h4>
<a id="Q1-1-945"></a>
<a id="dx1-475001"></a>
<!--l. 20323--><p class="noindent">The <span class="cmbx-10">vgagl </span>driver is a fast linux console driver with full mouse and pm3d support. It looks at the environment
variable SVGALIB_DEFAULT_MODE for the default mode; if not set, it uses a 256 color mode with the highest
available resolution.
<!--l. 20328--></p><p class="noindent">Syntax: </p><pre class="prettyprint"><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;</span><span class="k">set</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;terminal</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;vgagl</span></span><span class="cmtt-10"><span class="p">&nbsp;\</span></span><span class="p">
